{%- comment -%}
  Customer account sidebar navigation — shared across main-account,
  main-addresses, and main-order so a signed-in customer sees the
  same shell everywhere and `aria-current` flips to the right link.

  Accepts:
  - current: {String} one of 'details' | 'addresses' | 'orders' | ''.
    The 'orders' value flags "I'm on the order detail screen, which
    is reached from the Details landing"; we mark Details active so
    the nav stays contextually anchored.

  Landmark pattern: outer <aside> carries the "complementary"
  landmark semantics, inner <nav> wraps the link group so screen
  readers announce "navigation" when the user lands on the links and
  "complementary" for the aside itself (WCAG 1.3.1 — navigational
  link lists belong inside a <nav>).

  Extracted from main-account.liquid / main-addresses.liquid to DRY
  the markup and to close the R11 gap where main-order.liquid had
  only a single "← Back to account" link and lost the sidebar shell
  when customers deep-linked to /account/orders/:id and refreshed.
{%- endcomment -%}
{%- liquid
  assign nav_current = current | default: ''
  # Treat the Order-detail view as "I'm in the Details area" for
  # active-link purposes — orders are surfaced from the account landing.
  assign is_details = false
  assign is_addresses = false
  if nav_current == 'details' or nav_current == 'orders'
    assign is_details = true
  endif
  if nav_current == 'addresses'
    assign is_addresses = true
  endif
-%}
<aside class="kt-account__nav" aria-labelledby="AccountSharedNavHeading">
  <h2 id="AccountSharedNavHeading" class="visually-hidden">{{ 'kt.customer.account.nav_label' | t }}</h2>
  <nav aria-label="{{ 'kt.customer.account.nav_label' | t }}">
    <a
      href="{{ routes.account_url }}"
      class="kt-account__nav-link{% if is_details %} kt-account__nav-link--active{% endif %}"
      {%- if is_details %} aria-current="page"{% endif -%}
    >
      {{ 'kt.customer.account.details' | t }}
    </a>
    <a
      href="{{ routes.account_addresses_url }}"
      class="kt-account__nav-link{% if is_addresses %} kt-account__nav-link--active{% endif %}"
      {%- if is_addresses %} aria-current="page"{% endif -%}
    >
      {{ 'kt.customer.account.addresses' | t }}
      <span class="kt-account__nav-count">{{ customer.addresses_count }}</span>
    </a>
    {%- comment -%}
      R91 — logout is now a POST form, not a GET <a>. GET-based
      logout is vulnerable to:
      - Browser link prefetchers (Chrome, Edge prefetch hovered links)
        accidentally signing the customer out
      - Pre-rendering / link-checker tools triggering logout
      - CSRF-style attacks via embedded `<img src="...account/logout">`
      The Shopify Skeleton convention is a real `{% form 'logout' %}`
      submit button styled as a link. The CSS rule
      `.kt-account__nav-link--logout` already styles the underlying
      element identically; native button reset is applied below.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- form 'logout' -%}
      <button type="submit" class="kt-account__nav-link kt-account__nav-link--logout kt-account__nav-link--button">
        {{ 'kt.customer.account.log_out' | t }}
      </button>
    {%- endform -%}
  </nav>
</aside>
